Diagnosis. Recognized by the distinctive body shape, with short, posteriorly acuminate elytra (
Fig. 11
).

Aedeagus total length 0.70 mm ; mainpiece length 0.43 mm ; mainpiece, in lateral view, distinctively narrowed just before distal widened area; flagellum long, forming spiral which is stiff for all but apical 1 / 4 , which is very weakly sclerotized and its shape can therefore vary depending on preparation; collar is in front of flagellum only, not wrapping around as in some species (
Fig. 22
)

Distribution. Presently known from extreme southern Cape Province (
Fig. 34
).
